[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there any reliable way to probe the amount of memory available for allocation? <code>Sys.free_memory()</code> is not enough, because if I understand things correctly, Julia's GC can keep memory around that is available for allocation within the Julia process, but not available for the OS.</p>\n<p>I've tried to make an MVE to investigate this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Julia console\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">using</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Random</span>\n\n<span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Base</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">format_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Sys</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">free_memory</span><span class=\"p\">())</span>\n<span class=\"go\">\"58.672 GiB\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"n\">zeros</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">UInt8</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">50_000</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">for</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">i</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">in</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"mi\">400_000</span><span class=\"p\">];</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c\"># Alloc many chunks</span>\n\n<span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"n\">randperm</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">length</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"p\">))[</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"mi\">40_000</span><span class=\"p\">]];</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c\"># Keep some random chunks</span>\n\n<span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Base</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">format_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Sys</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">free_memory</span><span class=\"p\">())</span>\n<span class=\"go\">\"39.935 GiB\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">GC</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">gc</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nb\">true</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Base</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">format_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Sys</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">free_memory</span><span class=\"p\">())</span>\n<span class=\"go\">\"39.935 GiB\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Base</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">format_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Base</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">summarysize</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"p\">))</span>\n<span class=\"go\">\"1.864 GiB\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nb\">nothing</span>\n\n<span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">GC</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">gc</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nb\">true</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"gp\">julia&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Base</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">format_bytes</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Sys</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">free_memory</span><span class=\"p\">())</span>\n<span class=\"go\">\"41.208 GiB\"</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>For some reason, Julia doesn't return the memory to the system, even though I've removed everything I've allocated. I'm fine with that. <span aria-label=\"slight smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f642\" role=\"img\" title=\"slight smile\">:slight_smile:</span>  But I would like to check how much memory that Julia has claimed and I cannot find any function for doing that.</p>",
        "id": 591719397,
        "sender_full_name": "Rasmus Henningsson",
        "timestamp": 1777451307
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think Julia has functionality for that. I would imagine that information is in the system malloc implementation.</p>",
        "id": 591783848,
        "sender_full_name": "Jakob Nybo Andersen",
        "timestamp": 1777466532
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, I see. So maybe I could ask the system somehow how much memory the Julia process uses and subtract  Base.gc_live_bytes() from that.<br>\nIt wouldn't be perfect either, because any malloc call not tracked by the GC would be counted incorrectly.</p>",
        "id": 591796767,
        "sender_full_name": "Rasmus Henningsson",
        "timestamp": 1777469458
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"285705\">Rasmus Henningsson</span> has marked this topic as resolved.</p>",
        "id": 591875165,
        "sender_full_name": "Notification Bot",
        "timestamp": 1777489318
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My experience with this is that it can be very platform specific. For example, if you are using HPC, it might be better to ask the scheduler rather than the system.</p>",
        "id": 591882801,
        "sender_full_name": "Mark Kittisopikul",
        "timestamp": 1777491673
    }
]